snippet.textDisplay: I’d like to point out that just because when Ethan is hanging, he doesn’t hit the ground, doesn’t mean that when he’s falling, he’s not going to hit the ground. When he’s hanging, there’s no motion because the gravitational force acting downwards is equal to the spring force acting upwards. When he’s falling, he’ll have a downward velocity and move past this equilibrium point. Anyone who watches a spring oscillate up and down and see the spring move below it’s resting/equilibrium position.
snippet.textOriginal: I’d like to point out that just because when Ethan is hanging, he doesn’t hit the ground, doesn’t mean that when he’s falling, he’s not going to hit the ground. When he’s hanging, there’s no motion because the gravitational force acting downwards is equal to the spring force acting upwards.
